# Home Lab Setup

## Objective
This project documents the virtualization environment I built on Apple
Silicon to practice IT administration, troubleshooting, and networking.
It serves as the foundation for all my other lab projects — a safe
space to install, configure, break, and repair systems the way a help
desk or sysadmin would in a real environment. Building this on an ARM
Mac also gave me hands-on exposure to ARM64 architecture, which is
increasingly common in cloud and enterprise environments.

## Environment

**Host machine**
- Mac mini (M1, 2020)
- Chip: Apple M1 (ARM64, 8-core)
- Memory: 8 GB unified memory
- Startup disk: Macintosh HD
- Host OS: macOS Ventura 13.7.6
- Hypervisor: Oracle VirtualBox [version] (Apple Silicon / ARM build)

**Guest VMs**
| VM Name       | OS                        | vCPU | RAM    | Disk  | Purpose                         |
|---------------|---------------------------|------|--------|-------|---------------------------------|
| UBUNTU-SRV01  | Ubuntu Server 22.04 ARM64 | 2    | 2-3 GB | 25 GB | Linux fundamentals & services   |
| WIN-CLIENT01  | Windows 11 ARM            | 2    | 4 GB   | 40 GB | Windows admin & troubleshooting |

> Note: With 8 GB of unified memory shared with macOS, I run **one VM
> at a time** and allocate resources based on the task. This constraint
> pushed me to be deliberate about resource management. In addition, 
I will be downloading the ISO on to a 1Tb Solid Sate Drive.

## Network Design

I configured the VMs using VirtualBox networking modes so they can
reach the internet for updates and, where needed, stay isolated from my
home network.

![Network diagram](screenshots/network-diagram.png)

- **NAT** — gives each VM internet access for patching and installs
  while keeping it behind the host
- **Host-only network** — lets VMs communicate privately or stay
  isolated for testing
- IP addressing: [record what VirtualBox assigns, e.g. 192.168.56.0/24
  on the host-only adapter]

## What I Did

1. Confirmed my host is Apple Silicon and downloaded the VirtualBox
   build for macOS / ARM64.
2. Installed VirtualBox and granted the required macOS security
   permissions (System Settings → Privacy & Security).
3. Downloaded ARM64 images from official sources and verified checksums:
   - Ubuntu Server 22.04 for ARM64
   - Windows 11 ARM
4. Created UBUNTU-SRV01 first (lightest footprint): performed a minimal
   Ubuntu Server install and configured SSH access.
5. Created WIN-CLIENT01: allocated resources, mounted the ARM installer,
   and completed a clean Windows 11 ARM installation.
6. Configured network adapters (NAT + host-only) on both VMs.
7. Took a baseline snapshot of each VM so I can roll back after breaking
   things in future labs.

