## What I Learned / Why It Matters

Setting up virtualization on Apple Silicon taught me how a single
physical machine can host multiple isolated systems, and it forced me
to understand the difference between ARM64 and x86 architectures — why
software has to be built for the right instruction set, and why I
couldn't just grab any ISO and expect it to boot. That's a concept many
help desk techs never actually confront until it bites them.

Understanding NAT versus host-only networking clarified how devices are
segmented and protected on a real network, which is exactly what a help
desk tech needs when diagnosing why a machine can't reach a resource.
Working within 8 GB of memory also made me deliberate about resource
allocation — a constraint that mirrors real budget-limited IT
environments.

## Challenges & How I Solved Them

- **Standard x86 ISOs wouldn't boot.** My first instinct was to grab a
  normal Windows/Ubuntu ISO, which failed on the M1. I learned that
  Apple Silicon requires ARM64 guest images and switched to the correct
  builds — a hands-on lesson in CPU architecture.
- **[Add a real one you hit.]** Describe the symptom, how you diagnosed
  it, and the fix. This section is where interviewers see how you think.

